\begin{theorem}
Let $L$ be finitely generated cosimplicial group and suppose that the space ${\textnormal{Hom}}(L_0,U(m))$ is path connected for all $m\geq 1$. Then, $B(L,U)$ is an $E_\infty$-ring space.
\end{theorem}
\begin{proof}
By Proposition \ref{prop2.3.1}, ${\textnormal{hocolim}}_{\mathbb{I}} B(L,U(\_))$ is an $E_\infty$-ring space. To show that this homotopy colimit is homotopy equivalent to $B(L,U)$,  first, note that the conjugation action of $\Sigma_n$ is homologically trivial since it factors through conjugation action on $U(m)$. Using \cite[~Theorem 11.12]{May 1} with our hypothesis, $|{\textnormal{Hom}}(L,U(m))|=B(L,U(m))$ is path connected for all $m\geq1$. The colimit $B(L,U)$ is also an $H$-space under block sum of matrices, and therefore abelian. 
\end{proof}

\begin{exam}
The property $\pi_0({\textnormal{Hom}}(L_0,U(m)))=0$ for all $m\geq1$, is satisfied by the cosimplicial groups $L=F/\Gamma^q$, $F/F^{(q)}$, $\overline{F}/\Gamma^q$, and $\overline{F}/F^{(q)}$ defined in Example \ref{example 1} and also for the surface groups $T_{*+1}$.
\end{exam}



